This is a bit of a hack but is more along the lines of what I was thinking (https://jsfiddle.net/873rkve1/2/):

The token `UNROLLED_LOOP_INDEX` is indiscriminately replaced with the loop index when unrolling a loop so using the token in a `#define` identifier results in a new indexed identifier for each loop. For example in this case `TEST_ARR_UNROLLED_LOOP_INDEX` is unpacked into `TEST_ARR_0`, `TEST_ARR_1`, and `TEST_ARR_2` for each loop iteration respectively. This effectively lets you access array values in preprocessor macros.

I'm not sure what the project will think of this, though, but it should be significantly cleaner and more maintainable than the sorted list approach being used now imo.

```js
defines: {
  TEST_ARR_0: 2,
  TEST_ARR_1: - 1,
  TEST_ARR_2: 0,
},
  
fragmentShader: /* glsl */`
  
  uniform sampler2D textures[ 3 ];
  
  void main() {
  
	  gl_FragColor = vec4( 0.0 );
	  gl_FragColor.a = 1.0;
  
	  #pragma unroll_loop_start
	  for ( int i = 0; i < 3; i ++ ) {
  
		  #if TEST_ARR_UNROLLED_LOOP_INDEX != - 1

		  gl_FragColor += texture( textures[ TEST_ARR_UNROLLED_LOOP_INDEX ], vec2( 0.5 ) );

		  #endif
  
	  }
	  #pragma unroll_loop_end
	  
  }
`
```

