`If` isn't a node, it is exported from the `ShaderNode.js`.

Also, you can use some TSL-specific syntax -- for example, you can write `oneMinus` and `reciprocal` instead of `sub( 1, ... )` and `div( 1, ... )`. You also don't need any `float` type casters (they are only used for explicitly converting one type to another, which isn't needed here). I also suggest you to use some more node chaining (this reduces the need to import anything apart from `tslFn` and `vec3` here). Also, it's better to not use any assigns (and `If`) when not strictly needed -- they doesn't allow the Nodes system to do as much symplifying as possible.

I would simplify this code to something like:
```js
const CommerceToneMappingNode = tslFn( ( { color, exposure } ) => {

 	const startCompression = 0.8 - 0.04;
 	const desaturation = 0.15; 

	color = color.mul( exposure );

 	const x = color.r.min( color.g, color.b );
 	const offset = x.lessThan( 0.08 ).cond( x.sub( x.mul( x, 6.25 ) ), 0.04 );

 	color = color.sub( offset );

 	const peak = color.r.max( color.g, color.b );

 	const d = startCompression.oneMinus();
 	const newPeak = d.mul( d ).div( peak.add( d.sub( startCompression ) ) ).oneMinus();

 	color = color.mul( newPeak.div( peak ) );

 	const g = desaturation.mul( peak.sub( newPeak ) ).add( 1 ).reciprocal().oneMinus();

 	return peak.lessThan( startCompression ).cond( color, g.mix( color, vec3( 1, 1, 1 ) ) );

 } );
```
Note that the last `cond` **currently** will generate previous nodes (`d`, `newPeak`, `g`) in any case, even if they aren't used in a clause -- you can temporary revert to using `If` so that wouldn't happen, but we plan to fix it in any case.

