It's also common for us to use automatic conversions, especially when dealing with vectors. This prevents the user from having to manually declare nodes for common conversions, simplifying the process. For example, if they add an `ivec2` or a `float`, it will be automatically converted to a `vec2`. This can also help avoid type checks.

```js
// using TSL function

export const mx_rotate2d = Fn( ( [ input, amount ] ) => {

	input = vec2( input );

	const radians = amount.mul( Math.PI / 180.0 );
	return rotate( input, radians );

} );

// using JS function (inline code)

export const mx_rotate2d = ( input, amount ) => {

	input = vec2( input );

	const radians = amount.mul( Math.PI / 180.0 );
	return rotate( input, radians );

};
```

